=====================================================================
CONSTRUCTION CHECKLIST — 1.0 N·m STEPPER-WINDER
=====================================================================

TOOLS REQUIRED
- Hacksaw, files, Dremel or angle grinder
- Drill + 8 mm bit, center punch
- M8 taps/dies if needed, adjustable wrench
- Calipers, ruler, protractor or printed 18° template
- Bench vise, hammer, pliers
- Multimeter, 12 V power supply
- Safety glasses + gloves

=====================================================================
PHASE 1 — FRAME & SHAFT (30–45 min)
=====================================================================

1. Cut two steel angle brackets to ~120 mm length.
   - Drill 8 mm holes for bearings, aligned vertically.
   - Ensure shaft will sit level (use level or calipers).

2. Press or epoxy 608 skate bearings into brackets.
   - Verify shaft spins freely with <0.5 mm wobble.

3. Insert 8 mm smooth-shank bolt as main shaft.
   - Thread one end with M8 die if needed.
   - Secure with nyloc nut on one side only (leave other end free for spring).

   [Frame]--[608]--------[Shaft 8 mm]--------[608]--[Frame]

=====================================================================
PHASE 2 — SLIP CLUTCH STACK (20 min)
=====================================================================

Assembly order on shaft (from bearing outward):

   Bearing → Fender washer (large OD)
          → Leather disc (cut from belt or shoe sole, 30–35 mm OD)
          → Ratchet wheel (see Phase 3)
          → Fender washer
          → Belleville washer (convex side toward nut)
          → M8 nyloc nut

1. Tighten nut until clutch slips at ~1.28 N·m.
2. Use calibration method:
   - Attach 100 mm lever arm to shaft.
   - Hang 1.3 kg weight (water bottle + sand).
   - Adjust nut until arm just slips at ~horizontal.
   - Lock with second nut or threadlocker.

Target FN ≈ 347 N — Belleville should be visibly compressed.

=====================================================================
PHASE 3 — RATCHET WHEEL FABRICATION (45–60 min)
=====================================================================

1. Start with 50 mm steel washer (or cut disc from plate).
2. Mark 20 teeth:
   - Print or draw circle with 18° increments.
   - Mark every 18° around perimeter.
3. Cut teeth:
   - File V-notches ~2–3 mm deep at each mark.
   - Or Dremel cutoff wheel for cleaner profile.
   - Deburr all edges thoroughly.
4. Drill 8 mm center hole if not present.
5. Test fit on shaft — should rotate with clutch but lock to shaft when driven.

Tooth profile (ASCII):
     /\
    /  \   ← 18° pitch, ~2.5 mm depth
   /    \

=====================================================================
PHASE 4 — PAWLS & SOLENOID (40–50 min)
=====================================================================

1. Drive Pawl:
   - Cut 3–4 mm thick steel strip ~60 mm long.
   - Bend one end into hook or file to engage ratchet tooth.
   - Pivot on small bolt or rivet near solenoid linkage.
   - Attach return spring (10–15 N) to pull pawl back.

2. Holding Pawl:
   - Similar strip, mounted on frame.
   - Spring-loaded to drop into teeth automatically.
   - Must allow forward rotation but block reverse.

3. Mount door-lock solenoid:
   - Align so plunger stroke pushes drive pawl ~10–12 mm.
   - Use steel linkage arm (bent coat hanger or rod) if needed.
   - Add limit stop so pawl over-travels by ~2 mm.

Top view alignment:
          [Holding Pawl] ↑
   Frame -------------------
               [RATCHET 20T]
   Frame -------------------
               ↓ [Drive Pawl] ← Solenoid

=====================================================================
PHASE 5 — MAINSPRING ATTACHMENT
=====================================================================

1. Attach spiral spring (tape measure or clock) to output side of shaft.
2. Secure inner end to shaft (pin or set screw).
3. Outer end fixed to frame or output drum.
4. Wind manually 1–2 turns to preload, then test ratchet steps.

=====================================================================
PHASE 6 — ELECTRONICS & WIRING
=====================================================================

- MOSFET (IRLZ44N): Gate to microcontroller pin, Source to GND.
- Flyback diode (1N5408) across solenoid terminals.
- 12–24 V supply (car battery or bench PSU).
- Optional: 100–220 µF capacitor across supply for clean pulse.

Typical pulse: 80–150 ms ON, then PWM hold at 30–50% if needed.

=====================================================================
PHASE 7 — CALIBRATION & TEST
=====================================================================

1. Verify slip clutch at 1.28–1.3 N·m with weight method.
2. Cycle 50 steps manually — check consistent advance, no double-step.
3. Measure torque output with lever + scale.
4. Run 100 automated steps — monitor heat on solenoid.
5. Adjust:
   - Pawl springs too weak → add tension.
   - Binding → file teeth or realign.
   - Over-slip → tighten Belleville nut.

=====================================================================
SAFETY & FINAL CHECKS
=====================================================================

- Wear eye protection — springs store energy.
- Keep fingers clear of ratchet during testing.
- Do not exceed 1.3 N·m slip limit.
- Secure all fasteners with threadlocker.
- Label "1.0 N·m MAX — TORQUE LIMITED"

